      <hedline>
        <hl1>No Energy Atonement</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Gutmann letter, replying to June 13 Op-Ed article, says people who criticize Americans for their heavy consumption of fuel overlook fact that much of that fuel is used by farmers who help feed good part of world's population</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Norbert Walter (''Gobbling Energy and Wasting It, Too,'' Op-Ed, June 13) joins the chorus of critics who condemn the United States as the world's largest consumer of energy and producer of pollution. Guilty as charged, Americans are supposed to scrap their sport utility vehicles and embrace the Kyoto Protocol.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Norbert Walter (''Gobbling Energy and Wasting It, Too,'' Op-Ed, June 13) joins the chorus of critics who condemn the United States as the world's largest consumer of energy and producer of pollution. Guilty as charged, Americans are supposed to scrap their sport utility vehicles and embrace the Kyoto Protocol.</p>
        <p>But the critics generally overlook a major factor behind our heavy energy consumption: as American farmers plow acreage and harvest, store and transport crops, they do burn a lot of gas, but they also feed a good part of the world's population.</p>
        <p>Americans can find good environmental reasons for conserving energy; atonement for some fancied gluttony should not be one of them.</p>
        <p>DAVID GUTMANN  Wallingford, Vt., June 13, 2001</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
